
00:00:00,357 --> 00:00:02,765
Narrator: Tonight on
"Shark Tank," Kendra Scott,

00:00:02,765 --> 00:00:05,394
the founder of powerhouse
jewelry brand Kendra Scott,

00:00:05,394 --> 00:00:06,628
returns to the Tank.

00:00:06,628 --> 00:00:07,696
I'm sitting
in front of you,

00:00:07,696 --> 00:00:10,932
somebody who built
a billion‐dollar brand

00:00:10,932 --> 00:00:12,768
out of their extra bedroom
of their house.

00:00:12,768 --> 00:00:15,670
I have just enough cash
in the bank to make it 30 days,

00:00:15,670 --> 00:00:16,671
or we're out of business.

00:00:16,671 --> 00:00:18,240
Oh.
You have picked a sector

00:00:18,240 --> 00:00:20,208
that it's almost impossible
to make money in.

00:00:20,208 --> 00:00:21,743
I want 20%
of the company.

00:00:21,743 --> 00:00:23,111
What a savage.

00:00:23,111 --> 00:00:25,447
I am going to offer you
my golden ticket.

00:00:25,447 --> 00:00:26,681
‐Whoo!
‐Oh!

00:00:26,681 --> 00:00:29,184
Find a nice barn,
and just go shoot it.

00:00:29,184 --> 00:00:32,287
I always love it when somebody
tells me I can't do something.

00:00:32,287 --> 00:00:34,856
So take that
and use it as fire.

00:00:39,861 --> 00:00:44,332
♪♪

00:00:44,332 --> 00:00:46,802
Narrator: First into the Tank
is a comfortable version

00:00:46,802 --> 00:00:48,437
of a fashion staple.

00:00:48,437 --> 00:00:53,508
♪♪

00:00:53,508 --> 00:00:58,547
♪♪

00:00:58,547 --> 00:01:00,749
Hi, Sharks.
My name is Haley Pavone,

00:01:00,749 --> 00:01:03,418
and I'm from
San Luis Obispo, California.

00:01:03,418 --> 00:01:06,121
Today, I'm seeking
a $500,000 investment

00:01:06,121 --> 00:01:09,958
in exchange for 5%
of my game‐changing company,

00:01:09,958 --> 00:01:11,226
Pashion Footwear.

00:01:11,226 --> 00:01:13,061
It's a tale as old as time.

00:01:13,061 --> 00:01:15,263
A woman puts on
her favorite pair of heels

00:01:15,263 --> 00:01:18,767
and heads out to work, out to
a wedding, or out for the night.

00:01:18,767 --> 00:01:20,936
She is absolutely
crushing her commute,

00:01:20,936 --> 00:01:24,806
tearing up that dance floor,
and looking her absolute best...

00:01:24,806 --> 00:01:26,408
for exactly 45 minutes.

00:01:26,408 --> 00:01:28,143
Suddenly,
her feet are on fire,

00:01:28,143 --> 00:01:31,413
and she is regretting everything
about her shoe choice.

00:01:31,413 --> 00:01:35,150
So I invented the ultimate
solution to high‐heel pain

00:01:35,150 --> 00:01:36,485
and inconvenience ‐‐

00:01:36,485 --> 00:01:39,788
the world's first
fully convertible high heels.

00:01:39,788 --> 00:01:42,357
Now, not that I'm not
totally crushing this outfit,

00:01:42,357 --> 00:01:45,594
but let me slip into something
just a little more comfortable.

00:01:45,594 --> 00:01:47,729
With a quick twist
of the wrist,

00:01:47,729 --> 00:01:50,098
our stylish high heels
turn into comfortable

00:01:50,098 --> 00:01:52,868
and practical flats
just like that.

00:01:52,868 --> 00:01:54,169
Corcoran: Wow.
Want to see me do it again?

00:01:54,169 --> 00:01:57,572
Yes, we do.
That's impressive.

00:01:57,572 --> 00:01:59,908
Whew!
That is so much more comfy.

00:01:59,908 --> 00:02:01,576
Here at Pashion,
we are determined

00:02:01,576 --> 00:02:03,311
to make traditional
high heels,

00:02:03,311 --> 00:02:06,248
and all their ridiculous
problems, a thing of the past.

00:02:06,248 --> 00:02:08,517
Now, Sharks,
who's ready to majorly disrupt

00:02:08,517 --> 00:02:10,519
the massive women's
footwear market

00:02:10,519 --> 00:02:12,220
and take the next step
of this journey

00:02:12,220 --> 00:02:14,789
in some awesome
convertible high heels?

00:02:14,789 --> 00:02:17,526
That's remarkable.
Now, I actually do have samples
for each of you.

00:02:17,526 --> 00:02:19,361
They're in your size.
Oh, good.

00:02:19,361 --> 00:02:21,530
You know
I love a good nude heel.

00:02:21,530 --> 00:02:23,198
Way to go, Haley.
There we go. Fantastic.

00:02:23,198 --> 00:02:24,699
Part of our key innovation

00:02:24,699 --> 00:02:26,801
is we use completely
different materials

00:02:26,801 --> 00:02:29,204
from any other high heel
in our midsole.

00:02:29,204 --> 00:02:30,739
They're totally flexible.

00:02:30,739 --> 00:02:33,575
When you have no body weight,
it looks like it has an arch,

00:02:33,575 --> 00:02:35,877
but the second you step down,
goes completely flat.

00:02:35,877 --> 00:02:37,512
So, I pop the heel off.

00:02:37,512 --> 00:02:40,415
Okay, now, am I supposed to
also remove something

00:02:40,415 --> 00:02:43,285
from right here?
Yes, you're removing
this sole‐support portion.

00:02:43,285 --> 00:02:45,053
Just grab it, turn,
and then pull out.

00:02:45,053 --> 00:02:46,621
There you go.
Ah, okay,
the whole piece is off.

00:02:46,621 --> 00:02:48,390
Yes. And that part
that you took out just there,

00:02:48,390 --> 00:02:49,925
that's the removable
sole support.

00:02:49,925 --> 00:02:52,227
That's really
the essence of our I. P.

00:02:52,227 --> 00:02:54,596
There have been
removable heels before...
Yes.

00:02:54,596 --> 00:02:56,331
...but no one's ever innovated
on a removable sole.

00:02:56,331 --> 00:02:57,866
So I'm going
to stand up on this.

00:02:57,866 --> 00:03:00,936
Ooh, wow.
It's, like, bouncy.

00:03:00,936 --> 00:03:04,205
Yeah, so to put them back on,
you just hook this bit here,

00:03:04,205 --> 00:03:06,207
pop it back in,
give it a twist,

00:03:06,207 --> 00:03:08,610
it'll click, and you're locked
back into place.

00:03:08,610 --> 00:03:11,212
Gotcha.
So I am assuming

00:03:11,212 --> 00:03:13,982
that you have sold
quite a few of these.
We have, yes.

00:03:13,982 --> 00:03:15,584
So, it's been a year
and some change,

00:03:15,584 --> 00:03:17,719
and we've done a little over
$800,000 in sales.

00:03:17,719 --> 00:03:19,087
Wow.
Now, that's impressive.

00:03:19,087 --> 00:03:20,822
What about returns?
And what are
the returns like?

00:03:20,822 --> 00:03:24,893
Yep.
So our return
and exchange percentage is 24%.

00:03:24,893 --> 00:03:27,896
24%?
Yes, the footwear average,
though, is 20%

00:03:27,896 --> 00:03:30,465
just because the sizing
for footwear is so difficult

00:03:30,465 --> 00:03:33,201
to make perfect online.
And your sales are net sales
after all returns?

00:03:33,201 --> 00:03:37,105
No, net sales ‐‐ $500,000.
$500,000. Okay, so ‐‐

00:03:37,105 --> 00:03:39,341
Every woman I know
hates her high heels,

00:03:39,341 --> 00:03:41,209
every one of them,
and can't walk in them

00:03:41,209 --> 00:03:42,510
for more than
three or four hours.

00:03:42,510 --> 00:03:44,412
Why was it you who said,

00:03:44,412 --> 00:03:46,114
"Let me do something
about this"?

00:03:46,114 --> 00:03:47,849
So, in my sophomore year
of college,

00:03:47,849 --> 00:03:49,784
I was out at
a sorority spring formal,

00:03:49,784 --> 00:03:52,554
and I'd worn six‐inch high
heels, as college girls do.

00:03:52,554 --> 00:03:54,856
But high heels
when you're trying to dance

00:03:54,856 --> 00:03:56,291
are not comfortable.

00:03:56,291 --> 00:03:58,593
It's really more of a wobble,
and I wanted to bust a move.

00:03:58,593 --> 00:04:00,829
So I ditched my high heels...
[ Laughs ]

00:04:00,829 --> 00:04:02,664
...and took to
the dance floor barefoot.

00:04:02,664 --> 00:04:05,734
Unfortunately,
tragedy and inspiration

00:04:05,734 --> 00:04:07,202
quite literally struck.

00:04:07,202 --> 00:04:09,704
One of the other young women
accidentally stomped

00:04:09,704 --> 00:04:10,939
her stiletto
through my foot...

00:04:10,939 --> 00:04:12,440
Oh.
...and impaled me
through the toe.

00:04:12,440 --> 00:04:14,242
Oh, my God.
O'Leary: Through the ‐‐
Are you kidding?

00:04:14,242 --> 00:04:15,910
Through the toe, yes.
Like, right through?

00:04:15,910 --> 00:04:17,646
Like, clean through.
This is a terrible story.

00:04:17,646 --> 00:04:19,414
And as I'm sitting on the side
of the dance floor,

00:04:19,414 --> 00:04:23,151
it struck me as odd that there
is this societal expectation

00:04:23,151 --> 00:04:26,054
for women to wear high heels to
formal or professional events.

00:04:26,054 --> 00:04:28,423
Everyone knows they hurt
and that they're inconvenient,

00:04:28,423 --> 00:04:30,258
and yet there is no solution.

00:04:30,258 --> 00:04:33,662
So, Haley, how have you gotten
your $500,000 in net sales?

00:04:33,662 --> 00:04:36,331
We are all online,
and we've been able to sell

00:04:36,331 --> 00:04:39,634
through digital marketing, P. R.,
and then also word of mouth.

00:04:39,634 --> 00:04:42,203
Haley,
you are super impressive.
Thank you.

00:04:42,203 --> 00:04:43,705
I want to hear your background
a little bit.

00:04:43,705 --> 00:04:45,874
Yes, absolutely.
So, when I was in college,

00:04:45,874 --> 00:04:48,209
I already was very much
in the headspace of,

00:04:48,209 --> 00:04:50,879
when I graduate,
I want to be working for myself.

00:04:50,879 --> 00:04:53,148
And so after
that impalement incident...
[ Chuckles ]

00:04:53,148 --> 00:04:56,384
...I dove in headfirst, started
pitching at different events,

00:04:56,384 --> 00:04:59,320
and actually raised
the first $26,500,

00:04:59,320 --> 00:05:02,257
and I actually got the first
working salesman samples

00:05:02,257 --> 00:05:04,726
the day before
my college graduation.

00:05:04,726 --> 00:05:05,760
‐Wow!
‐Wow! That's great.

00:05:05,760 --> 00:05:07,162
So they got
their first break‐in.

00:05:07,162 --> 00:05:09,097
Were you wearing your shoes
in that graduation picture?

00:05:09,097 --> 00:05:10,598
Yes, absolutely.
And luckily,

00:05:10,598 --> 00:05:13,568
I'd actually built the company
up enough at this point

00:05:13,568 --> 00:05:16,037
that when I graduated,
I was able to come on full‐time.

00:05:16,037 --> 00:05:17,839
I brought on
a footwear‐development team,

00:05:17,839 --> 00:05:19,140
hired on a COO,

00:05:19,140 --> 00:05:21,342
brought on a lot
of student volunteers, actually.

00:05:21,342 --> 00:05:24,012
All with $26,000?
Wow.
Yes. Initially.

00:05:24,012 --> 00:05:25,380
We have raised more
since then.

00:05:25,380 --> 00:05:27,449
Who owns your company now?
What's your cap table look like?

00:05:27,449 --> 00:05:28,650
I own my company right now.

00:05:28,650 --> 00:05:30,685
So, we've raised a total
of $2.5 million to date.

00:05:30,685 --> 00:05:31,553
Oh!
Scott: Wow!

00:05:31,553 --> 00:05:32,821
Corcoran: How much?
Whoa!

00:05:32,821 --> 00:05:35,457
$2.5 million,
all on convertible notes.

00:05:35,457 --> 00:05:37,726
So right now, I own
83% of the company.

00:05:37,726 --> 00:05:38,860
But after they convert?

00:05:38,860 --> 00:05:40,595
It depends, obviously,
on valuation.

00:05:40,595 --> 00:05:43,098
But for instance, if you were
to take my deal today,

00:05:43,098 --> 00:05:44,899
I would be at 45%.

00:05:44,899 --> 00:05:47,836
Oh, and you know that we're
going to have to negotiate,

00:05:47,836 --> 00:05:49,537
and so you're going to
end up owning,

00:05:49,537 --> 00:05:52,574
if you get a deal,
less than 45%.

00:05:52,574 --> 00:05:55,343
But I'm going to own a little
less of a much larger company

00:05:55,343 --> 00:05:57,245
with the help of a fabulous
Shark, right?
Which I'm always
a fan of,

00:05:57,245 --> 00:05:59,447
but how much cash
do you have left in the bank?

00:05:59,447 --> 00:06:01,683
Right now,
we have about $250,000.

00:06:01,683 --> 00:06:02,650
Ooh!
Yes.

00:06:02,650 --> 00:06:04,018
How much inventory
do you have?

00:06:04,018 --> 00:06:06,454
Right now, I have $150,000
worth of inventory at cost.

00:06:06,454 --> 00:06:07,922
What's your monthly burn?

00:06:07,922 --> 00:06:11,025
Our monthly burn right now is
about $90,000 before marketing.

00:06:11,025 --> 00:06:12,093
Ouch.

00:06:12,093 --> 00:06:14,696
Your burn is
$90,000 a month?
Yes.

00:06:14,696 --> 00:06:16,898
So you have
three months...
Mm‐hmm.

00:06:16,898 --> 00:06:19,000
...of cash left?
Yes.

00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:21,202
But, that being said, I've been
in this situation before,

00:06:21,202 --> 00:06:22,537
and I did get out of it.

00:06:22,537 --> 00:06:23,805
Something you should know
about me

00:06:23,805 --> 00:06:26,074
is I'm one of the most resilient
people you'll ever meet.

00:06:26,074 --> 00:06:28,109
Back in 2019,
we were in a situation

00:06:28,109 --> 00:06:32,147
where I found us $80,000 in debt
and I realized,

00:06:32,147 --> 00:06:35,016
"Okay, I have just enough cash
in the bank

00:06:35,016 --> 00:06:37,452
to make it 30 days,
or we're out of business."

00:06:37,452 --> 00:06:40,255
And so
I hit the ground running.

00:06:40,255 --> 00:06:42,857
I pitched every single person
that would listen,

00:06:42,857 --> 00:06:45,660
and I closed a million‐dollar
deal on the 30th day.

00:06:45,660 --> 00:06:47,295
And that's why we're still
in business today.

00:06:47,295 --> 00:06:50,732
So, yes, it's a scary situation,
but I believe in this too much

00:06:50,732 --> 00:06:52,567
to ever let it fail,
and I will get out of it.

00:06:52,567 --> 00:06:57,038
You don't really want to give up
more than 5% here.

00:06:57,038 --> 00:06:58,506
I mean,
I appreciate the value

00:06:58,506 --> 00:06:59,874
that a Shark brings
to the table.

00:06:59,874 --> 00:07:03,011
Alright, look, I would make you
an offer that looks like this.

00:07:03,011 --> 00:07:06,114
I give you the $500,000
for 5%.

00:07:06,114 --> 00:07:08,049
However,
I get paid a royalty

00:07:08,049 --> 00:07:11,920
till I recoup a million bucks,
and then that royalty goes away.

00:07:11,920 --> 00:07:14,022
And then the only negotiation
we have to have

00:07:14,022 --> 00:07:16,391
is how much
that royalty should be.

00:07:16,391 --> 00:07:19,460
I would like it to be
$5 a unit.

00:07:19,460 --> 00:07:21,329
I'm not super interested
in a royalty...
You don't know yet.

00:07:21,329 --> 00:07:23,631
...only because I want
every single dollar...
You don't know yet.

00:07:23,631 --> 00:07:26,234
...to go into growing this.
Wait.
Here's what's ridiculous.

00:07:26,234 --> 00:07:28,236
We don't even know
what they cost,

00:07:28,236 --> 00:07:30,371
and we don't know
what they cost to make, Kevin.

00:07:30,371 --> 00:07:33,575
Right now,
the product cost is $36,

00:07:33,575 --> 00:07:35,643
and then the landed cost
is $47,

00:07:35,643 --> 00:07:38,746
and we sell them for between
$150 and $190.

00:07:38,746 --> 00:07:40,715
You have plenty of room
for a $5 royalty.

00:07:40,715 --> 00:07:41,683
That's not a problem.

00:07:41,683 --> 00:07:43,384
I do, but I'd rather have
that $5

00:07:43,384 --> 00:07:45,019
go towards
growing the business.
You don't know yet,
Haley.

00:07:45,019 --> 00:07:47,922
Why don't you wait to see
how many other offers you get?
Okay.

00:07:47,922 --> 00:07:49,591
Corcoran: Haley, let me get
the ball going here.

00:07:49,591 --> 00:07:50,792
I think you're
the type of person ‐‐

00:07:50,792 --> 00:07:53,127
you don't know
what you don't know.
Sure.

00:07:53,127 --> 00:07:56,164
The most important part
of building a business

00:07:56,164 --> 00:07:57,565
is keeping it in line,

00:07:57,565 --> 00:08:00,101
and you stretch every buck
nine different ways

00:08:00,101 --> 00:08:01,803
to see what you can get
out of it.

00:08:01,803 --> 00:08:03,037
And I feel like
we <i>are</i> doing that.

00:08:03,037 --> 00:08:04,505
I mean, I know we have
a high burn...
I don't know.

00:08:04,505 --> 00:08:06,774
...but as I mentioned,
I don't have excessive overhead.

00:08:06,774 --> 00:08:08,209
You <i>do</i> have
excessive overhead.

00:08:08,209 --> 00:08:10,578
You're burning
$90,000 a month,

00:08:10,578 --> 00:08:12,313
you raised $2.5 million,

00:08:12,313 --> 00:08:14,315
and you have
three months left

00:08:14,315 --> 00:08:15,717
before you're out
of business.

00:08:15,717 --> 00:08:17,518
I would say
that's important.

00:08:17,518 --> 00:08:18,987
I can't take a chance
on your business,

00:08:18,987 --> 00:08:20,488
climbing those mountains
with you.

00:08:20,488 --> 00:08:22,090
So I'm sorry.
I'm out.

00:08:22,090 --> 00:08:23,258
Okay. Thank you.

00:08:23,258 --> 00:08:27,061
Yeah, Haley, you have
$150,000 worth of inventory.

00:08:27,061 --> 00:08:29,931
That's about $500,000
worth of revenue.

00:08:29,931 --> 00:08:33,301
That's another five‐and‐a‐half
months of survival,

00:08:33,301 --> 00:08:35,336
which then allows you
to create more cash flow

00:08:35,336 --> 00:08:36,838
to bring in
more inventory.

00:08:36,838 --> 00:08:39,240
If you told me,
"This is where we're at.

00:08:39,240 --> 00:08:40,675
I'm going to sell
these shoes

00:08:40,675 --> 00:08:43,011
because I need to focus
my attention to these things

00:08:43,011 --> 00:08:44,779
to sell those shoes,"
it'd be a different story,

00:08:44,779 --> 00:08:45,813
but that's not
where you're at.

00:08:45,813 --> 00:08:47,615
So for those reasons,
I'm out.

00:08:47,615 --> 00:08:49,017
Okay.
Thank you for your time.

00:08:49,017 --> 00:08:51,853
Haley, you are
a remarkable young woman,

00:08:51,853 --> 00:08:54,455
but the product
is worrying me a little bit.

00:08:54,455 --> 00:08:56,891
It felt very strange
to walk on.

00:08:56,891 --> 00:08:59,360
So I don't know,
if I was walking

00:08:59,360 --> 00:09:01,763
several blocks in New York City,
for example,

00:09:01,763 --> 00:09:03,031
in between meetings,

00:09:03,031 --> 00:09:04,432
if that really
would be something

00:09:04,432 --> 00:09:05,967
that would be
comfortable for me.

00:09:05,967 --> 00:09:09,103
I know you are going to be
a success in life,

00:09:09,103 --> 00:09:11,606
but this, I'm not
100% sold on.

00:09:11,606 --> 00:09:15,043
I wish you the best of luck,
but I'm out.

00:09:15,043 --> 00:09:16,344
Thank you.
I appreciate that.

00:09:16,344 --> 00:09:19,614
So, Haley, I ‐‐
I think it's clever.

00:09:19,614 --> 00:09:20,782
It's a good idea.

00:09:20,782 --> 00:09:22,050
It's great for QVC.

00:09:22,050 --> 00:09:24,252
I think you ‐‐ Maybe.
[ Chuckles ]

00:09:24,252 --> 00:09:28,823
I think it's good quality,
but $500,000 for 5%,

00:09:28,823 --> 00:09:30,358
it's just not enough
for me.

00:09:30,358 --> 00:09:32,026
And I don't think
$500,000's

00:09:32,026 --> 00:09:34,362
going to be enough money
for you.
I mean,
I'm open to negotiating.

00:09:34,362 --> 00:09:35,630
But as an investment,

00:09:35,630 --> 00:09:37,298
it doesn't make sense
for me right now.

00:09:37,298 --> 00:09:39,200
So I'm sorry. I'm out.

